# CEO Review (Plan) — Sanctuary: Worship Playback Engine

## Verdict reasoning
Plan is genuinely good enough to build a winning richness-10 demo. All 9 client pain points map 1:1 to real, working Web Audio features (not UI shells), backed by a 12-file architecture, a credible scheduler reference (Wilson 25ms/100ms), and a sample-lock approach confirmed by research. Programmatic OfflineAudioContext stem generation is the correct call — kills licensing risk and keeps the demo self-contained. Design direction (dark stage-console, amber/blue, Inter + JetBrains Mono) is exactly the DAW/FOH language this client uses daily. plan-eval passed all 5 criteria with sound justification.

## Problems (non-blocking, carried forward)
1. **Audio realism is the single make-or-break for THIS audience.** A trained worship audio engineer / DJ client will judge the demo on whether stems sound musical, not just whether the graph wires up. Bare sine/saw will read as a toy. demo-builder MUST layer/detune oscillators, tune ADSR envelopes, add light filtering, and make the two songs actually sound like distinct worship arrangements. This is a build-quality bar to enforce at build-ceo, not a plan gap.
2. **Browser-vs-desktop gap** — client's product is a desktop app; demo is browser. proposal-writer must explicitly bridge (Web Audio AudioWorklet ≈ native audio thread, AudioContext ≈ CoreAudio session) so the demo reads as transferable domain skill, not a different platform.
3. **Michael's specific credibility hooks underused in plan** — St. Olaf music degree, DAWs since 5th grade, wedding-DJ obsession with perfect audio, and the production MIDI-bridge Python program he uses live at gigs are the strongest proof points for "real-time audio engineer." Plan correctly defers these to proposal-writer; flagging so they are not dropped — the MIDI-bridge especially is direct evidence of real-time signal-processing competence and should be a headline in the cover letter.

None of these require re-planning. The plan is build-ready as written.

## handoff
- produced: CEO approval of the plan at richness 10; 3 carry-forward notes for downstream steps
- decisions: PASS plan as-is; no revision/redirect; programmatic audio + Wilson scheduler + stage-console design all approved
- next needs: demo-builder — implement the FULL Web Audio graph for all 9 points (no mocks) and make synthesized stems sound genuinely musical (layered/detuned osc, tuned envelopes); build-ceo must enforce audio-realism bar
- risks: synthesized stems sounding crude to an expert-audio client; proposal-writer must (a) bridge browser-vs-desktop and (b) foreground Michael's St. Olaf degree + wedding-DJ + production MIDI-bridge program

VERDICT: pass
